Awesome Timeline Visualization¶

  • A Timeline is a graphical way of displaying a list of events in chronological order.
  • line + scatter + stem plot

Simple Explanation¶

  • First of all, the ingredients are:

    • a line
    • 3 data points
      • 2 point set of date
        • black one, white one
      • 1 point set of time
    • vertical lines which matching with time (stem plot)

  • The downside is that the process of adjusting text position is heuristic.

from datetime import datetime


tl_dates = [
    "WED April 10",
    "SUN April 14",
    "MON April 15",
    "THU April 18"
]

tl_x = [1, 2, 6, 9]

tl_sub_x = [1.5, 2.4, 2.9, 3.4, 3.8, 4.5, 5.0, 6.5, 7, 7.6, 8]
tl_sub_times = [
    "1:30 PM",
    "9:00 AM",
    "1:42 PM",
    "7:15 PM",
    "10:00 PM",
    "11:30 PM",
    "11:40 PM",
    "12:20 AM",
    "12:45 AM",
    "2:00 AM",
    "2:20 AM",
]

tl_text = [
    "Titanic sets sail.",
    "Recieve Message.",
    "Baltic Warns Titanic\nof icebergs.", 
    "Smith requests the\n return of the message.",
    "Second Officer\n Lightroller is\n relievced from duty.",
    "Warning bells, iceberg\n sighting.",
    "Titanic hits an iceberg.",
    "Life boats are being\n lowered.",
    "Passengers slowly arrive\n on deck.",
    "Rear of boat begins to\n raise.",
    "Titanic sinks."
]

# Set figure & Axes
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 5), constrained_layout=True)
ax.set_ylim(-2, 2)
ax.set_xlim(0, 10)


# Timeline : line
ax.axhline(0, xmin=0.1, xmax=0.95, c='#0000ff', zorder=1)
# Timeline : Date Points
ax.scatter(tl_x, np.zeros(len(tl_x)), s=120, c='#4a4a4a', zorder=2)
ax.scatter(tl_x, np.zeros(len(tl_x)), s=30, c='#008000', zorder=3)
# Timeline : Time Points
ax.scatter(tl_sub_x, np.zeros(len(tl_sub_x)), s=50, c='#4a4a4a',zorder=4)

# Date Text
for x, date in zip(tl_x, tl_dates):
    ax.text(x, -0.2, date, ha='center', 
            fontfamily='serif', fontweight='bold',
            color='#4a4a4a')
    

# Stemplot : vertical line
levels = np.zeros(len(tl_sub_x))    
levels[::2] = 0.3
levels[1::2] = -0.3
markerline, stemline, baseline = ax.stem(tl_sub_x, levels, use_line_collection=True)    
plt.setp(baseline, zorder=0)
plt.setp(markerline, marker=',', color='#4a4a4a')
plt.setp(stemline, color='#008000')

# Text
for idx, x, time, txt in zip(range(1, len(tl_sub_x)+1), tl_sub_x, tl_sub_times, tl_text):
    ax.text(x, 1.3*(idx%2)-0.5, time, ha='center', 
            fontfamily='serif', fontweight='bold',
            color='#4a4a4a' if idx!=len(tl_sub_x) else '#e3120b', fontsize=11)
    
    ax.text(x, 1.3*(idx%2)-0.6, txt, va='top', ha='center', 
        fontfamily='serif',color='#0000ff' if idx!=len(tl_sub_x) else '#e3120b')

# Spine
for spine in ["left", "top", "right", "bottom"]:
    ax.spines[spine].set_visible(False)

# Ticks    
ax.set_xticks([]) 
ax.set_yticks([]) 

# Title
ax.set_title("Titanic Timeline", fontweight="bold", fontfamily='serif', fontsize=16, color='#e3120b')

plt.show()

Awesome Distribution Visualization (Ridgeplot)¶

  • A Ridgeline plot (sometimes called Joyplot) shows the distribution of a numeric value for several groups.
    • library : matplotlib, seaborn
    • colortheme from movie "Snowpiercer" (because of class)

Simple Explanation¶

  • Step1 : Use Gridspec
  • Step2 : Create density plot using seaborn's kdeplot
    • bw : bandwidth
    • edgecolor : to separate each density plot
    • alpha : remove transparency
    • cut : clear meaning
  • Step3 : Remove ticks & labels except last xticks
  • Step4 : Remove Spine
  • Step5 : Make plots closer & Make the background transparent
  • Step6 : add subtext (figure title, axes title)

# sample DataFrame 
np.random.seed(0)
data = pd.DataFrame({
    'Pclass': np.random.choice([1, 2, 3], size=500),
    'Age': np.random.uniform(0, 85, size=500)
})

# Ensure the 'Pclass' column exists
if 'Pclass' not in data.columns or 'Age' not in data.columns:
    raise ValueError("DataFrame must contain 'Pclass' and 'Age' columns")

# figure and subplots
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
gs = fig.add_gridspec(3, 1)
gs.update(hspace=-0.55)

axes = []
colors = ["#1f77b4", "#d62728", "#ff7f0e"]
for idx, cls in enumerate(sorted(data['Pclass'].unique())):
    axes.append(fig.add_subplot(gs[idx, 0]))
    
    # Plot KDE for each class
    sns.kdeplot(x='Age', data=data[data['Pclass'] == cls], 
                fill=True, ax=axes[idx], cut=0, bw_adjust=0.25, 
                lw=1.4, edgecolor='lightgray', color=colors[idx], alpha=1) 
    
    # Set limits and ticks
    axes[idx].set_ylim(0, 0.04)
    axes[idx].set_xlim(0, 85)
    axes[idx].set_yticks([])
    if idx != 2:
        axes[idx].set_xticks([])
    axes[idx].set_ylabel('')
    axes[idx].set_xlabel('')
    
    # Hide spines
    for spine in ["top", "right", "left", "bottom"]:
        axes[idx].spines[spine].set_visible(False)
        
    axes[idx].patch.set_alpha(0)
    axes[idx].text(-0.2, 0, f'Pclass {cls}', fontweight="light", fontfamily='serif', fontsize=11, ha="right")

# Add a main title
fig.text(0.13, 0.81, "Age distribution by Pclass in Titanic", fontweight="bold", fontfamily='serif', fontsize=16)

plt.show()

np.random.seed(0)
data = pd.DataFrame({
    'Age': np.random.uniform(0, 85, size=500),
    'Survived': np.random.choice([0, 1], size=500)
})
# Define the age band function
def age_band(num):
    for i in range(1, 100):
        if num < 10 * i:
            return f'{(i - 1) * 10} ~ {i * 10}'

# Apply the age band function
data['age_band'] = data['Age'].apply(age_band)
# Calculate survival rates
titanic_age = data[['age_band', 'Survived']].groupby('age_band')['Survived'].value_counts().sort_index().unstack().fillna(0)
titanic_age['Survival rate'] = titanic_age[1] / (titanic_age[0] + titanic_age[1]) * 100

# Plotting
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(10, 7))
# Update color_map to use previous colors
color_map = ['#1f77b4' for _ in range(len(titanic_age))]  # Blue
color_map[0] = color_map[-1] = '#d62728' 

ax.bar(titanic_age['Survival rate'].index, titanic_age['Survival rate'], 
       color=color_map, width=0.55, 
       edgecolor='black', 
       linewidth=0.7)
# Remove spines
for s in ["top", "right", "left"]:
    ax.spines[s].set_visible(False)

# Annotation Part
for i in titanic_age['Survival rate'].index:
    ax.annotate(f"{titanic_age['Survival rate'][i]:.02f}%", 
                xy=(i, titanic_age['Survival rate'][i] + 2.3),
                va='center', ha='center', fontweight='light', 
                color='#4a4a4a')

# Mean line and annotation
mean = data['Survived'].mean() * 100
ax.axhline(mean, color='black', linewidth=0.4, linestyle='dashdot')
ax.annotate(f"Mean: {mean:.2f}%", 
            xy=('70 ~ 80', mean + 4),
            va='center', ha='center',
            color='#4a4a4a',
            bbox=dict(boxstyle='round', pad=0.4, facecolor='#efe8d1', linewidth=0))

# Title & Subtitle    
fig.text(0.06, 1, 'Age Band & Survival Rate', fontsize=15, fontweight='bold', fontfamily='serif')
fig.text(0.06, 0.96, 'It can be seen that the survival rate of young children and the elderly is high.', fontsize=12, fontweight='light', fontfamily='serif')

# Y-axis ticks and grid
grid_y_ticks = np.arange(0, 101, 20)
ax.set_yticks(grid_y_ticks)
ax.grid(axis='y', linestyle='-', alpha=0.4)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Awesome Bar+Scatter Plot (Stripplot)¶

  • A strip plot is a scatter plot where one of the variables is categorical.
  • color theme : Pantone 1805, Pantone 540

Simple Explanation¶

  • Calculate mean first
  • Generate Uniform Distribution
    • Survived = 1, Survived = 0
  • Make a difference using color or luminance or transparency.
  • (tips) Add legend
  • (tips) Add explanation under the title.

np.random.seed(0)
data = pd.DataFrame({
    'Sex': np.random.choice(['male', 'female'], size=500),
    'Survived': np.random.choice([0, 1], size=500)
})

# Calculate mean survival rate by sex
survival_rate = data.groupby('Sex').mean()[['Survived']]

# Extract survival rates for male and female
male_rate = survival_rate.loc['male']
female_rate = survival_rate.loc['female']

# Display the survival rates
print(survival_rate)
print(f"Male Survival Rate: {male_rate['Survived']:.2f}")
print(f"Female Survival Rate: {female_rate['Survived']:.2f}")

data = pd.DataFrame({
    'A': np.random.rand(100),
    'B': np.random.rand(100),
    'C': np.random.rand(100),
    'D': np.random.rand(100)
})
corr = data.corr()

# Define a custom color map with blue, red, yellow, and green
colors = ["blue", "green", "yellow", "red"]
n_bins = 100  # Number of bins for the colormap
cmap_name = "custom_cmap"

# Create a colormap from the colors
cmap = mcolors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list(cmap_name, colors, N=n_bins)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(8, 8))

# Create a mask for the upper triangle
mask = np.zeros_like(corr, dtype=bool)
mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask)] = True

# Create the heatmap with annotations and color bar
sns.heatmap(corr, 
            square=True, 
            mask=mask,
            annot=True,         # Add annotations to each cell
            fmt=".2f",         # Format of annotations
            linewidths=2.5, 
            vmax=1.0, vmin=-1.0, 
            cmap=cmap, 
            cbar=True,         # Show color bar
            cbar_kws={"shrink": .8},  # Adjust color bar size
            ax=ax)

# Customize tick labels
ax.set_yticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), fontfamily='serif', rotation=0, fontsize=12)
ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), fontfamily='serif', rotation=90, fontsize=12)

# Customize spines
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(True)
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['left'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['bottom'].set_visible(False)

# Add title and author text
fig.text(0.97, 1, 'Correlation Heatmap Visualization', fontweight='bold', fontfamily='serif', fontsize=15, ha='right')    
fig.text(0.97, 0.92, 'Dataset : Titanic\nAuthor : Subin An', fontweight='light', fontfamily='serif', fontsize=12, ha='right')    

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Awesome Dimension Reduction + Scatter Plot¶

  • UMAP(Dimension Reduction) + Scatterplot

Simple Explanation¶

In the past, dimensional reduction has been widely used in multidimensional data analysis.

However, it is seldom used to analyze it after clustering.

This visualization draws separate graphs based on gender and Pclass based on the clustering results according to survival, so that the distribution of survivors according to the criteria can be viewed differently.

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from umap import UMAP

# Load the dataset
file_path = r"C:\Users\rites\OneDrive\Desktop\gender_submission.csv"
data = pd.read_csv(file_path)

# Fill missing values and preprocess columns
data = data.fillna(0)

# Dimension Reduction with UMAP
data_sub = data.drop(['Survived', 'Ticket', 'Name', 'Cabin'], axis=1, errors='ignore')
umap_model = UMAP(random_state=0)
titanic_umap = umap_model.fit_transform(data_sub)

# Initialize subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 3, figsize=(15, 15))

# Plot 'Survived'
if 'Survived' in data.columns:
    axes[0][0].scatter(titanic_umap[data['Survived'] == 1][:, 0], titanic_umap[data['Survived'] == 1][:, 1], c='dodgerblue', alpha=0.6, edgecolors='w', s=60, label='Survived: 1')
    axes[0][0].scatter(titanic_umap[data['Survived'] == 0][:, 0], titanic_umap[data['Survived'] == 0][:, 1], c='firebrick', alpha=0.6, edgecolors='w', s=60, label='Survived: 0')
else:
    axes[0][0].scatter(titanic_umap[:, 0], titanic_umap[:, 1], c='gray', alpha=0.6, edgecolors='w', s=60, label='No Survival Data')

axes[0][0].set_title('Survived', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')

# Plot 'Sex'
if 'Sex' in data.columns:
    axes[1][0].scatter(titanic_umap[data['Sex'] == 0][:, 0], titanic_umap[data['Sex'] == 0][:, 1], c='seagreen', alpha=0.6, edgecolors='w', s=60, label='Male')
    axes[1][1].scatter(titanic_umap[data['Sex'] == 1][:, 0], titanic_umap[data['Sex'] == 1][:, 1], c='gold', alpha=0.6, edgecolors='w', s=60, label='Female')
else:
    axes[1][0].scatter(titanic_umap[:, 0], titanic_umap[:, 1], c='gray', alpha=0.6, edgecolors='w', s=60, label='No Sex Data')

axes[1][0].set_title('Gender: Male', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
